      "heading": "Days 5-6: The New Orleans Loop via St. Francisville – Plantations, Jazz, and Jambalaya",
      "paragraphs": [
        "<p>Another early start, because we’ve got a lot of ground to cover and a lot of soul to absorb. Today's 'return-trip' takes us south towards New Orleans, with a crucial and charming stop along the way. From Natchez, you’ll take US-61 South. This stretch of Highway 61 is much different from the Delta section; it's greener, more winding, and genuinely picturesque, often flanked by ancient oak trees and historic markers. Expect the drive to St. Francisville to take about <b>1 hour</b>.</p><p>St. Francisville, Louisiana, is a gem. It’s a small, historic town with a rich past, offering a gentler introduction to Louisiana’s plantation country before the sensory overload of New Orleans. For lunch, grab a bite at <b>The Francis Southern Table & Bar</b> for some upscale Southern comfort food in a beautiful setting. After lunch, choose your plantation. I recommend <a href=\"https://www.rosedown.org/\">Rosedown Plantation State Historic Site</a>. Its stunning gardens and well-preserved interiors offer a comprehensive look at plantation life. Alternatively, <a href=\"https://www.crt.state.la.us/louisiana-state-parks/historic-sites/a-fton-villa-gardens/index\">Afton Villa Gardens</a> (check seasonal openings) or <a href=\"https://www.crt.state.la.us/louisiana-state-parks/historic-sites/audubon-state-historic-site/index\">Oakley Plantation</a> (John James Audubon's former residence) are also excellent choices. Don't try to cram in too many; pick one or two and truly experience them. Skip any plantation that feels overly commercialized or glosses over the difficult parts of history; Rosedown does a decent job of balance.</p><p>After St. Francisville, it’s back on US-61 South, which eventually merges into I-110 S and then I-10 East towards New Orleans. This part of the drive, especially the interstate sections, is purely functional. Power through it. Expect the drive from St. Francisville to New Orleans to take about <b>1.5 to 2 hours</b>. As you approach the city, the landscape changes dramatically, giving way to urban sprawl, then the unique architecture of NOLA. You absolutely, unequivocally, MUST stay overnight in New Orleans. Attempting a round trip from Natchez in one day is lunacy and a disservice to one of America's greatest cities. Book a hotel in the French Quarter for the classic experience (<b>Hotel Monteleone</b> or <b>Hotel Provincial</b>), or consider the Garden District for something a bit quieter and stately (like the <b>Pontchartrain Hotel</b>), or the Warehouse District for a more modern, artsy vibe (<b>The Old No. 77 Hotel & Chandlery</b>). Check in, drop your bags, and hit the streets.</p><p>For your first NOLA evening, immerse yourself. Wander the French Quarter, let the sounds of jazz spill from the doorways, and find a spot for dinner. <b>Galatoire’s</b> or <b>Commander's Palace</b> are iconic but require reservations and a jacket; for something more accessible but still fantastic, try <b>Coop's Place</b> for classic Cajun/Creole fare (get the rabbit and sausage jambalaya) or <b>Central Grocery & Deli</b> for a muffuletta (take-out only, but a NOLA staple). Afterwards, find some live music. Preservation Hall is legendary, but you can also just walk down Frenchmen Street and hop between clubs. Let the city carry you.</p><p><b>Day 6</b> is your New Orleans deep dive. Start with coffee and beignets at <a href=\"https://cafedumonde.com/\">Cafe Du Monde</a>, then a stroll through Jackson Square. If you’re into military history, the <a href=\"https://www.nationalww2museum.org/\">National WWII Museum</a> is world-class and requires several hours. Alternatively, take a streetcar ride up St. Charles Avenue to explore the beautiful Garden District, admiring the grand mansions. For lunch, try <a href=\"https://www.domilises.com/\">Domilise's Po-Boy & Bar</a> for an authentic New Orleans po'boy experience, or <a href=\"https://www.datdog.com/\">Dat Dog</a> for something fun and quirky. Don't skip the <a href=\"https://www.neworleans.com/things-to-do/music/history-of-new-orleans-music/jazz-history/\">New Orleans Jazz National Historical Park</a> for a dose of musical history. Depending on how much you want to squeeze in, start your drive back to Natchez in the mid-to-late afternoon. The drive back (I-10 W to US-61 N) will take approximately <b>2.5 to 3 hours</b>. You'll arrive back at the Big Muddy Inn late, but filled with the vibrant energy of New Orleans and the serene calm of the Mississippi River. Grab a late-night snack in Natchez if you're still hungry, or just crash, dreaming of beignets and blues.</p>"
      ]
